              "text": "The expressions e to the i x and cosine of x plus i times the sine of x are actually two different ways of writing the exact same thing. This relationship is a fundamental part of complex analysis known as Euler's formula.\n\nThe first expression, e to the i x, uses the base of the natural logarithm raised to an imaginary power. This represents a point on a circle in the complex plane with a radius of one.\n\nThe second expression, cosine of x plus i times the sine of x, breaks that same point down into its horizontal and vertical components. The cosine of x represents the horizontal position on the real axis, and the sine of x represents the vertical position on the imaginary axis.\n\nIn summary, there is no numerical difference between them. They are equivalent. The exponential form is often used because it makes multiplication and division easier to calculate, while the trigonometric form is used to see the specific coordinates of the point on a graph.",
